1
00:00:01,667 --> 00:00:07,674
So I'd like to say a few words about the second noble truth now, which is the truth of the cause of suffering.

2
00:00:08,474 --> 00:00:13,019
And in the Buddha's words, what is the noble truth of the origin of suffering?

3
00:00:13,259 --> 00:00:19,745
It is craving which renews being and is accompanied by relish and lust, relishing this and that.

4
00:00:20,586 --> 00:00:26,032
In other words, craving for sensual desires, craving for being, craving for non-being.

5
00:00:27,413 --> 00:00:30,155
But where on does this craving arise and flourish?

6
00:00:31,503 --> 00:00:37,393
Wherever there is that which seems lovable and gratifying, thereon it arises and flourishes.

7
00:00:39,136 --> 00:00:41,719
There is this noble truth of the origin of suffering.

8
00:00:42,601 --> 00:00:48,070
Such was the vision inside wisdom, knowing and light that arose in me about things not heard before.

9
00:00:49,954 --> 00:00:55,063
And this noble truth must be penetrated by abandoning the origin of suffering.

10
00:00:59,009 --> 00:01:04,615
So we have three sources of suffering that the Buddha describes there.

11
00:01:05,557 --> 00:01:07,338
One is sense pleasures.

12
00:01:08,480 --> 00:01:14,507
So all the lovely sights and sounds, you know, here in the countryside, good food.

13
00:01:15,269 --> 00:01:25,742
And then remembering that sense pleasures also includes all the pleasures of the mind, you know, good conversations, good discussions, a detective story, if you like detective story, any sort of happy thoughts.

14
00:01:27,341 --> 00:01:29,365
And of course, the opposite is implied there.

15
00:01:29,385 --> 00:01:34,495
If we like the pleasant stuff, we also then want to get rid of the unpleasant stuff.

16
00:01:34,575 --> 00:01:41,289
So pain, irritating noises, unpleasant tastes and smells and so on.

17
00:01:41,468 --> 00:01:46,819
And of course, all the unhappiness of the mind, depression and fear and unhappy thoughts of all descriptions.

18
00:01:49,010 --> 00:02:09,752
craving is um the word used in that particular suit often is called desire desire presents pleasure sometimes called lust you know lust presents pleasures so craving desire lost that wanting you know you could describe it as wanting what's lovely not wanting what's horrible there's also this secondary is that craving to be

19
00:02:10,187 --> 00:02:16,013
So that's a craving to be somebody, you know, we want to be, for example, recognised.

20
00:02:16,633 --> 00:02:17,675
We want to be valued.

21
00:02:18,594 --> 00:02:19,735
We want to be respected.

22
00:02:19,756 --> 00:02:24,099
So all of those make us feel good.

23
00:02:24,379 --> 00:02:26,842
You know, they really give us a boost in our life.

24
00:02:28,084 --> 00:02:32,306
And we can get these around family, for example, you know, if we're identified with our family.

25
00:02:32,326 --> 00:02:38,693
For example, the role as a parent, you know, that can give a lot of joy and pride and happiness.

26
00:02:39,212 --> 00:02:42,776
And it can make the hard work involved in being a parent worthwhile.

27
00:02:42,796 --> 00:02:44,579
It can make sense of life.

28
00:02:44,618 --> 00:02:45,580
There's a role in life.

29
00:02:45,620 --> 00:02:46,721
There's a meaning to my life.

30
00:02:47,001 --> 00:02:49,243
I am a father or a mother, for example.

31
00:02:50,645 --> 00:02:53,889
So that can provide great joy in life.

32
00:02:53,929 --> 00:02:55,050
And these are real joys.

33
00:02:55,090 --> 00:02:59,114
The Buddha doesn't in any way say don't enjoy life.

34
00:02:59,253 --> 00:03:08,223
There's a list of the various happinesses, and one of them would be looking after family, looking after family and friends, looking after children, cherishing children.

35
00:03:09,959 --> 00:03:13,343
Another area where we identify with would be our jobs.

36
00:03:13,764 --> 00:03:28,644
So there again, we can really crave that sense of recognition around being somebody with a skill, being somebody with a trade, somebody who belongs to some organisation, somebody with some expertise.

37
00:03:28,663 --> 00:03:39,038
So all of that, the craving to be an expert, to be a really good whatever it is, carpenter, plumber, whatever it is,

38
00:03:40,873 --> 00:03:53,263
our hobbies as well if you know we want to be the best of course Gardiner the best bridge player and so on so this is all the area of craving to be and it would include friendships for example you know to be a friend to have friends

39
00:03:53,445 --> 00:03:55,068
So that gives us a lot of comfort.

40
00:03:55,448 --> 00:03:57,531
It helps our sense of self-worth.

41
00:03:58,312 --> 00:04:01,896
And again, this can be used very, very skillfully along the spiritual path.

42
00:04:02,818 --> 00:04:07,122
But it's just to see where we are also allowing it to draw us into suffering.

43
00:04:07,644 --> 00:04:17,495
You know, that real neediness for maybe our friends to always be available, for example, or a terrible anxiety about our friends because we can't live without them.

44
00:04:19,517 --> 00:04:23,783
So all these desires can be used skillfully to support us along the path.

45
00:04:25,324 --> 00:04:28,588
It's another huge desire, of course, the desire to be enlightened.

46
00:04:29,428 --> 00:04:32,331
That can really get in our way here.

47
00:04:32,351 --> 00:04:47,449
And Chögyam Trungpa, the Tibetan Buddhist master, he would call that spiritual materialism, that we're getting our status out of spiritual matters, maybe instead of houses and homes and stuff like that, but we're getting our

48
00:04:47,665 --> 00:04:50,752
sense of self-worth from spiritual progress.

49
00:04:51,353 --> 00:04:54,238
That can be an area which can cause huge suffering as well.

50
00:04:54,420 --> 00:04:55,762
So it's just to be aware of it.

51
00:04:57,346 --> 00:04:59,872
So they're all the craving to be.

52
00:04:59,911 --> 00:05:02,939
And you can probably think of many, many more examples.

53
00:05:03,660 --> 00:05:05,403
And then there's the craving not to be.

54
00:05:05,637 --> 00:05:08,920
So that'll be all the areas that we don't want to be identified with.

55
00:05:09,199 --> 00:05:10,302
For example, failure.

56
00:05:10,461 --> 00:05:14,084
Most of us would dread the thought of being seen as the failure.

57
00:05:14,646 --> 00:05:21,833
So we tend to hide our mistakes, gloss over our mistakes, even pretend to ourselves that we didn't make them somehow or other.

58
00:05:21,872 --> 00:05:26,377
And Joseph Goldstein just has a nice story around that.

59
00:05:26,437 --> 00:05:35,526
In one of his interviews with his teacher, Upan Dita, he was, without really having made a decision to kind of

60
00:05:35,927 --> 00:06:01,091
report his practice as a tiny little bit better than it was he just he realized afterwards he was doing that he had a sense of what he should be seeing at this stage of his meditation practice after so many years and so on and how equanimous he should be and how many insights he should have so that was coloring the way he was reporting everything and just at the end of the interview Upendita said that's not true

61
00:06:03,805 --> 00:06:09,690
At the end of a nice, long, embroidered, flowing interview of lots of spiritual success.

62
00:06:10,732 --> 00:06:11,432
That's not true.

63
00:06:12,012 --> 00:06:16,937
So Joseph Colstein just said he wanted the floor to open up and take him in.

64
00:06:17,218 --> 00:06:18,899
He was so embarrassed.

65
00:06:18,918 --> 00:06:19,579
It was terrible.

66
00:06:20,060 --> 00:06:27,266
So he spent days just struggling with embarrassment and self-judgment of all descriptions.

67
00:06:28,709 --> 00:06:33,052
And realizing, as soon as it was said, he realized he'd been exaggerating.

68
00:06:33,673 --> 00:06:42,461
Anyway, at the end of about two days of pure agony, he was able to just see, OK, the mind does this as well.

69
00:06:42,482 --> 00:06:44,504
That's another aspect of the human mind.

70
00:06:44,704 --> 00:06:46,045
You know, we want to be a success.

71
00:06:46,846 --> 00:06:48,387
And that's what it does.

72
00:06:48,447 --> 00:06:51,089
It pretends that it's a little bit better than it is.

73
00:06:52,011 --> 00:06:56,173
So he was able to see himself more humorously from then on.

74
00:06:56,634 --> 00:06:58,877
So it was, in that sense, a very good lesson for him.

75
00:07:00,398 --> 00:07:03,680
So he never took himself quite so seriously after that.

76
00:07:03,661 --> 00:07:27,980
because the human mind plays all kinds of tricks it's really uh it really is very devious so we don't want to be a failure also the whole area of employment you know it's often our first question what do you do you know when we meet someone what do you do so you know to have to say well i'm unemployed you know that's a bit of a come down our

77
00:07:28,500 --> 00:07:32,824
In certain social circles, then, you know, to be a janitor is a come down.

78
00:07:33,105 --> 00:07:35,288
So you just don't want to have to say all of that.

79
00:07:35,327 --> 00:07:42,134
So the whole area of employment, we might really be embarrassed about our employment or our lack of employment.

80
00:07:43,035 --> 00:07:49,261
And that can become a big source of stress for us, not wanting to be seen in certain social lights.

81
00:07:51,523 --> 00:07:58,389
So there is really so much stress built into the human condition, wanting to be a success, not wanting to be a failure.

82
00:07:58,824 --> 00:08:03,290
wanting to be accepted and not to blame ourselves for all of this.

83
00:08:04,430 --> 00:08:11,358
We can again hear the second noble truth, you know, desire is the cause of suffering and then start blaming ourselves for having all these desires.

84
00:08:12,319 --> 00:08:17,725
It's a very easy mistake for us to make and it's a mistake I find myself in again and again.

85
00:08:17,745 --> 00:08:27,297
So I find it helpful instead to kind of reflect on the whole condition and to generate some compassion around it.

86
00:08:27,276 --> 00:08:30,721
So all of these desires would be part of our survival strategy.

87
00:08:30,901 --> 00:08:38,893
And again, this probably comes from our evolution, just as we were mentioning before, that in order to survive, we need to thrive.

88
00:08:39,293 --> 00:08:51,770
You know, we need the good stuff in life so we can thrive on things like good food, good education, a safe space as a home, maybe with a nice garden in the countryside or something like that.

89
00:08:52,312 --> 00:08:55,697
So all those pleasant sounds, pleasant sights,

90
00:08:55,677 --> 00:09:03,846
a sense of, you know, good social status, the good food, all of that kind of thing, the safety, all of that would allow us to thrive.

91
00:09:04,706 --> 00:09:08,770
So naturally, you know, naturally our self wants to thrive.

92
00:09:09,672 --> 00:09:13,294
So those desires are built in to our system.

93
00:09:13,936 --> 00:09:18,301
It's not that they're our fault, you know, or that we're wrong for having desires.

94
00:09:18,321 --> 00:09:21,985
They're very, they're essentially, you know, survival strategies.

95
00:09:22,044 --> 00:09:23,405
So in that sense, they are wise.

96
00:09:24,870 --> 00:09:29,980
So all of those that promote health and well-being, a sense of confidence, a sense of self-worth.

97
00:09:30,500 --> 00:09:32,323
So certainly not to be despised.

98
00:09:35,028 --> 00:09:42,160
So to generate compassion around that whole area of desire, you know, just to keep reflecting desires are natural.

99
00:09:42,221 --> 00:09:45,307
And a lot of them can be used for good, as we were mentioning before.

100
00:09:45,727 --> 00:09:48,852
It's a question of deciding which ones to follow and which ones not to follow.

101
00:09:51,279 --> 00:09:53,923
So there is this teaching desire causes dukkha.

102
00:09:54,102 --> 00:09:58,187
There is maybe the tendency then to judge desire is wrong and to suppress it.

103
00:09:58,528 --> 00:10:00,311
But that is just another desire.

104
00:10:00,551 --> 00:10:02,052
You know, that's the desire for enlightenment.

105
00:10:03,114 --> 00:10:05,918
You know, the suppression of desire in order to get to the end of suffering.

106
00:10:06,599 --> 00:10:08,100
So that's a vicious circle.

107
00:10:08,341 --> 00:10:09,062
It can't work.

108
00:10:10,663 --> 00:10:15,229
It's an easy mistake, but we just have to see it again and again and keep dropping it.

109
00:10:17,470 --> 00:10:18,530
But what can we do?

110
00:10:18,551 --> 00:10:25,821
So what the Buddha says is this noble truth must be penetrated by abandoning the origin of suffering.

111
00:10:26,662 --> 00:10:30,788
So we have to abandon our, often we use the word, let go of desire.

112
00:10:33,010 --> 00:10:35,934
So we can acknowledge the desire.

113
00:10:36,437 --> 00:10:43,631
And especially here in meditation, we don't have to fulfill our desires, but we can just really acknowledge them, feel them if possible.

114
00:10:44,374 --> 00:10:52,590
So that way we're not suppressing, we're allowing the desire just to express itself in our minds and our bodies, but we're not indulging it.

115
00:10:53,532 --> 00:10:56,436
So it's the middle way between suppression and indulgence.

116
00:10:57,658 --> 00:11:06,150
And, you know, if we feel the desire to rush, you know, the Mahasi technique asks us to do everything slowly and we just feel really the desire to just rush through that door.

117
00:11:06,851 --> 00:11:17,086
And then can we feel that desire and feel the way it propels our body forward and instead just see, can we relax, take it easy, open the door slowly.

118
00:11:18,207 --> 00:11:22,053
So that's, again, allowing the desire, the impatience, you know, for our

119
00:11:22,607 --> 00:11:25,410
getting here, there and everywhere, that desire to burn out.

120
00:11:26,292 --> 00:11:29,335
We have the desire to gobble our dinner, just get through it quick.

121
00:11:30,296 --> 00:11:51,518
And again, if we can just feel that desire, acknowledge it, so not make ourselves wrong for it, but just acknowledge it and let it be felt in the body as maybe the shoulders wanting to move, the hands wanting to move in order to get the next spoonful in, the jaws wanting to chew quickly, everything like that.

122
00:11:51,937 --> 00:12:02,272
Just notice all of the tension associated with that desire and yet slowing down, relaxing as best we can and not following the desire.

123
00:12:02,351 --> 00:12:05,235
So again, that's just letting the desire burn itself out.

124
00:12:07,018 --> 00:12:10,523
So that's our middle path, our work here.

125
00:12:10,543 --> 00:12:16,071
And we can also just listen to our thoughts.

126
00:12:16,945 --> 00:12:18,226
I want another biscuit.

127
00:12:19,048 --> 00:12:23,894
It's so easy to come in and say, dismiss that, that's a stupid thought, you know, and we can just put it away.

128
00:12:23,913 --> 00:12:30,482
But if we listen to it, okay, I do want another biscuit and allow it to be felt, you know, really listen to it.

129
00:12:30,942 --> 00:12:37,471
So it's a kinder way of being with desire to really listen to those thoughts and realize that's what's happening.

130
00:12:37,491 --> 00:12:38,192
There is a desire.

131
00:12:38,452 --> 00:12:44,421
You might even feel somewhere in the body that is kind of grasping itself around that thought of another biscuit.

132
00:12:45,110 --> 00:12:46,731
I want to go to bed.

133
00:12:46,812 --> 00:12:54,302
So again, just listening to that, really listening into it, feeling the wish to go to bed with interest in the feeling.

134
00:12:55,104 --> 00:13:03,076
We're taking off the interest in going to bed, that dream of how lovely bed will be, but instead it's the interest in the here and now, the feeling of wanting to go to bed.

135
00:13:04,597 --> 00:13:12,990
So listening attentively to our own desires rather than quickly answering them with a put-down of some form.

136
00:13:14,759 --> 00:13:17,703
allowing ourselves to be human, to have all these desires.

137
00:13:21,350 --> 00:13:24,274
Of course, then there is the whole area of suppression of desire.

138
00:13:24,695 --> 00:13:26,357
You know, we can't just stop that either.

139
00:13:26,538 --> 00:13:29,844
We can't just turn off the suppressive forces within us.

140
00:13:29,903 --> 00:13:31,567
They're probably very, very deep habits.

141
00:13:32,187 --> 00:13:34,972
So again, it's a question of listening to those as best we can.

142
00:13:35,033 --> 00:13:36,754
And that can be hard.

143
00:13:36,936 --> 00:13:38,599
Well, I find it anyway, quite hard.

144
00:13:38,639 --> 00:13:41,322
So the suppressive forces

145
00:13:41,658 --> 00:13:46,506
would often involve a very stern crossness somewhere.

146
00:13:46,586 --> 00:13:50,514
So just tuning in to where in my body is stern or cross.

147
00:13:51,115 --> 00:13:52,658
And for me, I find it in the forehead.

148
00:13:52,739 --> 00:13:56,525
And sometimes, yes, sometimes around the back of the neck, the jaws, all of that.

149
00:13:56,566 --> 00:14:02,417
So all of that is trying to almost clamp down on these desires for more biscuits or wanting to go to bed.

150
00:14:03,038 --> 00:14:15,490
So to tune in to the suppressive forces as well, and again, listen to them, you know, the quick giving out, the quick answer back to any desire like I want a biscuit.

151
00:14:16,091 --> 00:14:17,352
And it says, no, you don't.

152
00:14:18,052 --> 00:14:18,514
You've had enough.

153
00:14:19,033 --> 00:14:23,058
Just to notice those little quick reactionary thoughts and maybe feel into them.

154
00:14:24,120 --> 00:14:32,168
So that's listening and acknowledging to the kind of control freak in us, which is a strong, strong, strong force within us.

155
00:14:32,653 --> 00:14:38,702
And linked to that there can be a lot of shame, you know, shame at our own imperfections, hating imperfections.

156
00:14:39,504 --> 00:14:43,129
Again, it'll be linked to probably fear of failure, fear of judgment, all of that.

157
00:14:43,629 --> 00:14:49,839
So they're going deep within us and they need a lot of tender acknowledgement, a lot of compassion, a lot of sympathy.

158
00:14:51,922 --> 00:15:01,075
So it's a long and patient process, really, being with this human condition that has so many desires built into it.

159
00:15:01,460 --> 00:15:06,265
It's very interesting that there is so many different desires and they're often in conflict with one another.

160
00:15:06,765 --> 00:15:10,530
You know, the desire for the biscuit and then immediately, no, you don't want a biscuit.

161
00:15:10,551 --> 00:15:15,417
And other desires like we want to be liked by everybody, but we also want to have our own way.

162
00:15:15,456 --> 00:15:23,105
Thanissara Bhikkhu, he has a whole series on selves and not self, he calls it.

163
00:15:23,125 --> 00:15:24,548
It's a wonderful little series.

164
00:15:25,539 --> 00:15:33,267
If you remember, each desire, as we were saying last night, each desire has the effect that our whole being goes into this idea of self.

165
00:15:33,908 --> 00:15:36,791
An idea of self is born in order to fulfil the desire.

166
00:15:36,831 --> 00:15:42,756
So every desire brings up some other aspect of ourselves, some other aspect of our personality.

167
00:15:43,417 --> 00:15:50,024
So it can be the kind of little whingy child who wants another biscuit, or it can be the stern schoolteacher who's saying, no, you've had enough.

168
00:15:50,845 --> 00:15:53,386
So he likens our condition as

169
00:15:53,788 --> 00:15:54,669
We're like a committee.

170
00:15:54,750 --> 00:15:55,530
We're not a person.

171
00:15:55,572 --> 00:15:56,253
We're a committee.

172
00:15:57,875 --> 00:16:04,403
And we're a committee at loggerheads with one another, you know, one member shouting at the other.

173
00:16:04,543 --> 00:16:10,172
And often, you know, a lot is going on under the scenes.

174
00:16:10,253 --> 00:16:14,158
You know, we're not very honest because we actually don't know ourselves that well.

175
00:16:14,197 --> 00:16:20,106
There's an awful lot of subconscious poking of ourselves going on here.

176
00:16:20,126 --> 00:16:21,028
So...

177
00:16:21,397 --> 00:16:32,836
It's not even a committee, it's more like a corrupt town council, he says, where people are taking bribes from each other and stabbing each other in the back and so on.

178
00:16:33,277 --> 00:16:44,636
So we really have a bit of a job with all these conflicting desires and somehow trying to survive in the midst of all of this is no joke.

179
00:16:55,264 --> 00:17:00,351
Now, one other possibility we have here is to see the detail of the arising of desire.

180
00:17:00,371 --> 00:17:08,223
So desire is born from either pleasant or unpleasant feeling.

181
00:17:09,685 --> 00:17:15,032
And the feeling then, if you remember, is just the recognition of some sense impression as being pleasant or unpleasant.

182
00:17:15,914 --> 00:17:20,260
So we smell the food, for example, at dinner.

183
00:17:20,961 --> 00:17:22,503
And so that's a pleasant aroma.

184
00:17:22,837 --> 00:17:26,242
And that would lead to the desire, OK, I want to get stuck into this now.

185
00:17:26,942 --> 00:17:35,795
And then, you know, the self is created in order to just get stuck in, to pick up the spoon and shove it into our mouth and get going on eating it.

186
00:17:36,777 --> 00:17:50,634
So if we can notice all of that, the aroma and then the sudden way the system is ready to eat, you know, the tension, you know, in the muscles ready to pick up knives and forks and so on.

187
00:17:51,307 --> 00:18:05,977
So if we can see that and just stop, just let it go, just stop, don't act on the desire and let it all die away and instead what you'll have at some stage, a little bit later when the system has relaxed, will be again the pleasant aroma.

188
00:18:07,098 --> 00:18:10,445
And can you stay at that level of a pleasant aroma

189
00:18:11,809 --> 00:18:17,661
You know, if we practice it, the desire then is just letting itself burn out.

190
00:18:17,721 --> 00:18:22,490
And if we can stay at that level of just pleasant vedana, life is so peaceful.

191
00:18:23,172 --> 00:18:26,598
We don't have the urgency of desire.

192
00:18:26,699 --> 00:18:32,028
We don't have the stress of a self being created to fulfill them all.

193
00:18:33,696 --> 00:18:49,326
The Buddha says this is really how we let suffering die away, is that we stay at the level of sense contact and vedana, of knowing our sense impressions, knowing whether they're pleasant or unpleasant, but allowing desires to fade away.

194
00:18:51,347 --> 00:18:52,349
And they do burn away.

195
00:18:52,811 --> 00:18:55,878
So it's really for us to see that, that desires do burn.

196
00:18:55,919 --> 00:18:57,021
They do just fade away.

197
00:18:57,162 --> 00:19:01,393
If we don't indulge them, if we don't suppress them, they just burn away.

198
00:19:01,452 --> 00:19:02,255
It's very interesting.

199
00:19:02,635 --> 00:19:05,803
Now, they come up again a second later, and you have to let that one burn away.

200
00:19:06,865 --> 00:19:08,529
So it's a patient process.

201
00:19:08,797 --> 00:19:22,134
But to see at least one, just that it dies away and I could be with this dinner even for a few moments with just the pleasure and no stress, no need to hurry, just appreciating.

202
00:19:23,076 --> 00:19:32,829
That's an example of the peaceful life we could live and we will all live when we come to the end of suffering, when we abandon all our desires.

203
00:19:39,053 --> 00:19:51,445
So I just want to leave this with the reminder that we don't have to judge ourselves wrong for having desires.

204
00:19:51,506 --> 00:19:54,229
We can use desires skillfully to get to the end of suffering.

205
00:19:54,890 --> 00:20:00,336
It's a conversation between Ananda and somebody else.

206
00:20:02,518 --> 00:20:07,423
A Brahmin, anyway, is asking Ananda, what is the way to the end of suffering?

207
00:20:14,018 --> 00:20:19,763
For what purpose, Master Ananda, is the holy life lived under the Buddha, the ascetic Gautama?

208
00:20:21,445 --> 00:20:27,251
It is for the sake of abandoning desire, Brahman, that the holy life is lived under the Blessed One.

209
00:20:28,893 --> 00:20:30,955
But, Master Ananda, is there a path?

210
00:20:31,276 --> 00:20:33,377
Is there a way for the abandoning of this desire?

211
00:20:34,598 --> 00:20:35,861
There is a path, Brahman.

212
00:20:36,040 --> 00:20:38,202
There is a way for abandoning of this desire.

213
00:20:40,065 --> 00:20:41,967
But, Master Ananda, what is the path?

214
00:20:42,487 --> 00:20:44,630
What is the way for abandoning of this desire?

215
00:20:46,172 --> 00:20:55,744
Here, Brahman, Abhiggu develops the basis for spiritual power that possesses concentration due to desire and volitional formations of striving.

216
00:20:57,748 --> 00:21:03,075
He develops the basis for spiritual power that possesses concentration due to energy and so on.

217
00:21:03,095 --> 00:21:04,977
He goes through a whole lot more of them.

218
00:21:06,920 --> 00:21:08,362
This, Brahman, is the path.

219
00:21:08,382 --> 00:21:10,704
This is the way for the abandoning of this desire.

220
00:21:11,528 --> 00:21:20,096
So just notice that what Ananda is saying, that we develop the basis for spiritual power due to desire.

221
00:21:20,116 --> 00:21:24,922
You know, we desire our spiritual progress.

222
00:21:25,422 --> 00:21:28,585
We use that desire to develop our spiritual powers.

223
00:21:30,227 --> 00:21:31,868
So it's a bit of a conundrum, isn't it?

224
00:21:31,888 --> 00:21:33,911
We're using desire to get to the end of desire.

225
00:21:34,932 --> 00:21:36,953
You know, we're striving to get to the end of striving.

226
00:21:38,154 --> 00:21:39,896
So anyway, the Brahman picks him up on this.

227
00:21:40,176 --> 00:21:40,978
He says...

228
00:21:41,785 --> 00:21:44,949
Such being the case, Master Ananda, the situation is interminable.

229
00:21:45,489 --> 00:21:49,134
It is impossible that one can abandon desire by means of desire itself.

230
00:21:51,836 --> 00:21:55,981
And so Ananda answers, Well then, Brahman, I'll question you about this matter.

231
00:21:56,502 --> 00:21:57,463
Answer as you see fit.

232
00:21:58,885 --> 00:22:00,047
What do you think, Brahman?

233
00:22:00,067 --> 00:22:02,911
Did you earlier have the desire, I will go to the park?

234
00:22:04,132 --> 00:22:07,516
And after he went to the park, did this corresponding desire subside?

235
00:22:08,096 --> 00:22:09,919
He went to the park to meet Ananda.

236
00:22:11,299 --> 00:22:12,741
So the Brahman answers, yes, sir.

237
00:22:14,743 --> 00:22:17,626
Did you already arouse energy thinking, I will go to the park?

238
00:22:18,248 --> 00:22:21,171
And after he went to the park, did the corresponding energy subside?

239
00:22:21,692 --> 00:22:22,211
Yes, sir.

240
00:22:24,234 --> 00:22:25,736
And he goes through them all like that.

241
00:22:25,776 --> 00:22:28,638
He aroused volitional formations as well to go to the park.

242
00:22:29,200 --> 00:22:31,122
So he strove to go to the park.

243
00:22:31,142 --> 00:22:32,304
He desired to go to the park.

244
00:22:32,324 --> 00:22:33,345
He strove to go to the park.

245
00:22:33,384 --> 00:22:34,125
He got to the park.

246
00:22:34,465 --> 00:22:35,747
But then they all subsided.

247
00:22:36,729 --> 00:22:40,732
So desires just subside after they've been fulfilled.

248
00:22:41,236 --> 00:22:44,199
or if we just watch them and let them burn out anyway.

249
00:22:45,840 --> 00:22:50,165
So we can therefore just let the desires we want to fulfil be fulfilled.

250
00:22:50,326 --> 00:22:51,507
Our desire is to meditate.

251
00:22:52,028 --> 00:22:54,550
We can act on those, we can allow those be fulfilled.

252
00:22:56,112 --> 00:23:00,017
Our desire to come and retreat, we can strive like mad to go and retreat.

253
00:23:01,317 --> 00:23:05,923
And that desire, that striving will just pass away when we go on to retreat.

254
00:23:07,124 --> 00:23:10,567
So we don't have to be afraid of our desirous nature.

255
00:23:11,189 --> 00:23:14,693
you know, our striving nature, but we can use it in the right direction.

256
00:23:17,277 --> 00:23:20,480
So anyway, the Brahman is eventually completely convinced.

257
00:23:21,583 --> 00:23:23,565
Ananda asks him, well, what do you think now, Brahman?

258
00:23:24,286 --> 00:23:26,489
Is the situation terminable or interminable?

259
00:23:27,490 --> 00:23:32,537
Surely, Master Ananda, such being the case, the situation is terminable, not interminable.

260
00:23:32,997 --> 00:23:34,499
Magnificent, Master Ananda.

261
00:23:35,820 --> 00:23:41,127
From today, let Master Ananda remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.

262
00:23:44,585 --> 00:23:56,769
So although desire is the cause of suffering, this is a gradual path and we use our desire to come to the end of suffering to get us to the end of suffering.

263
00:24:01,519 --> 00:24:02,019
Thank you.

